<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-594-413  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 594 413.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 25 1990 n1237 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A case of too much method? (Software methodologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davidson, Clive.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Software methodologies are becoming increasingly complex and maybecome too technical for end-users, according to a report fromInput.andP;  The report cites computer aided systems engineering (Case)tools as increasing the problem, because of their tendency toautomate the faults of methodologies.andP;  An industry source notesthat case tools introduce efficiency, but the fault lies in theover-extension of automation.andP;  The methods that are being usedwere devised for highly structured softwares such as payroll oraccounting systems, but problems today are more complex, dynamic,and open-ended, according to the report.andP;  Suppliers of methods,disagree, noting that methodology tends to make things simplisticfor the end-user.andP;  A supplier states that methods have thefunction of focusing on the user's role and the essentials ofrectifying things.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software EngineeringMethodsComputer-Aided Software EngineeringProblem ComplexityManagement ApplicationsReportsIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>